  description: "asyncio.TimeoutError and asyncio.InvalidStateError class identity checks in asyncioexc174timeoutinv namespace — asyncio.TimeoutError.__name__.__eq__('TimeoutError')==True ('TimeoutError'=12: 'Timeout'=7+'Error'=5=12; asyncio.TimeoutError IS the builtin TimeoutError — same Python object; asyncio.TimeoutError is builtins.TimeoutError is True; TimeoutError is a builtin subclass of OSError: TimeoutError > OSError > Exception > BaseException > object; MRO len=5); asyncio.TimeoutError.__module__.__eq__('builtins')==True (TimeoutError is defined in builtins because it IS the builtin; __module__=='builtins' confirms identity with the builtin TimeoutError); asyncio.InvalidStateError.__name__.__eq__('InvalidStateError')==True ('InvalidStateError'=17: 'Invalid'=7+'State'=5+'Error'=5=17; asyncio.InvalidStateError is defined in asyncio.exceptions — NOT the builtin); asyncio.InvalidStateError.__name__.__len__()==17 ('InvalidStateError'=17); asyncio.InvalidStateError.__module__.__eq__('asyncio.exceptions')==True (defined in Lib/asyncio/exceptions.py; raised when a Future or Task operation is called in an invalid state e.g. setting result on an already-completed Future); MRO ORDERING: CancelledError(3) < InvalidStateError(4) < TimeoutError(5); verified with Python 3.14.3"
